War, and thus of relatively little importance; it has therefore received little consideration from historians, a gap which this book remedies by reviewing the late Victorian Navy from a radically new perspective. It starts with the Great Near East crisis of 1878 and shows how itsaftermath in the Carnarvon Commission and its evidence produced a profound shift in strategic thinking, culminating in the Naval Defence Act of 1889; this evidence, from the ship owners, provides the definitive explanation of whythe Victorian Navy gave up on convoy as the primary means of trade protection in wartime, a fundamental question at the time. The book also overturns many assumptions about the era, especially the perception that the navy was weak, and clearly shows that the 1870s and early 1880s brought in crucial technological developments that made the Dreadnought possible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNaval art and sciencexHistoryy19th century. 0aNaval strategyxHistoryy19th century. 0aSea-powerzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aShipbuilding industryxMilitary aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aWarshipszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 4aMilitary History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh  aBritish naval history.  aLate Victorian Navy.  apre-Dreadnought era.  astrategic thinking.  atechnological developments.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615653340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846156533423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846156533/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles